   cd /tmp
       - wget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/kibana/kibana-8.18.4-amd64.deb
       - sudo dpkg -i kibana-8.18.4-amd64.deb

       - sudo nano /etc/kibana/kibana.yml

               - server.port: 5601         --> uncomment  
               -  server.host: "localhost"  --> uncomment
              -  sudo systemctl enable kibana
              - sudo systemctl status kibana

    - enter the http://localhost:5601   --> delete the cache browsing 

=========================================================================

    - curl -X GET "localhost:9200/_cat/indices?v"   -> to find the indexes

            output {
                elasticsearch {
                  hosts => ["http://localhost:9200"]
                  index => "apt_logs"     --> index name 
                }
           }
confirm the elastic search :-
       to check contains index exists and has documents or not

                  - curl -X GET "localhost:9200/apt_logs/_search?size=1&pretty"  

      - if u get the document then u want to create kibana 

formats of index pattern (creating index pattern):-

    apt_logs	logstash-*	❌ No
    apt_logs	  apt_logs  	✅ Yes
    apt_logs	  apt_*	      ✅ Yes
    apt_logs	  *	          ✅ Yes


- Go to Kibana (open in browser) :-
      - “Stack Management” → “Data Views”
          - Click "Create data view"
                - Name: apt_logs
                - Index pattern: apt_logs

 Now View the Logs:-
     -  Go to “Discover”
      - Select the data view: apt_logs
            - You’ll see the logs of apt 

 Kibana is now successfully displaying Logstash  data

              
